snippet.textDisplay:
0:59 the seatbelt is a backup for in case if the restraint breaks, which already has backup safety mechanisms inside
1:56 most parks make you pay for lockers. it sucks, but it's to keep the line moving as people don't need to go across the station to put their bag in a bin
2:35 ughhh. that's a perfectly safe drop as there are coasters with beyond vertical drop, and the manufacturer of it is one of the top 3 in the world.
7:05 that's a family coaster...
8:20 most breakdowns are because the safety mechanism spotted an error, and most new coasters break down often
10:16 you were just saying ow for the vid. don't lie
10:35 I've been on a coaster that goes from 0-120 mph in 3.8 seconds (top thrill dragster at Cedar Point) this is nothing
13:18 that's because it's a cloned ride, so they need to fit it in a tight footprint
anyways, I'm not hating, I'm just correcting some things so people don't think Roller Coasters are dangerous, because you have a 1 in 300,000,000 chance of actually dying on one, and a park wouldn't invest $20-30 million on an unsafe attraction.

snippet.textDisplay: Actually seatbelts (the strap that connects to the lap/shoulder restraint) on rollercoasters don’t do much. It’s almost impossible for the lap/shoulder restraint to release while the rollercoaster is in motion or not at the loading station (unless it’s manually done to free people from a broken down ride). The seatbelts are there to make riders feel safe on the ride and as a redundant safety feature
